Should Schools Teach Mindfulness?

Have you ever tried mindfulness or meditation, practices that focus on the present moment and being aware of your thoughts, feelings and bodily sensations? If so, what was it like for you? If not, does it sound like something you’d like to try? Do you think that such practices have a place in schools? Why or why not?

In my opinion,

ops.insert:
Should Schools Teach Mindfulness?
 
Have you ever tried mindfulness or meditation, practices that
focus on the present moment and being aware of your thoughts, feelings and
bodily sensations? If so, what was it like for you? If not, does it sound like
something you’d like to try? Do you think that such practices have a place in
schools? Why or why not?
 
---
 
In my opinion, these practices could potentially be useful
things to teach in school. Mindfulness and meditation can be incredibly
effective tools for self-regulation, stress reduction, and emotional
regulation. But I think it is important to consider the audience, in this case,
students, when considering how to implement teaching these practices. 
 
I am a teacher. But I am also a person who has a VERY hard time
being still. When trying to learn to practice mindfulness and meditation for
myself, I was taught that I needed to remain still so that I could focus. This
was extremely difficult and I found it counterproductive. I eventually found
success when my teacher adjusted the practice and allowed me to move along with
practice. This taught me that there is no one-size-fits-all approach to
teaching mindfulness. My problem was not with being aware of my thoughts,
feelings, or even bodily sensations. It was in what my body was doing at the
time. I tried a variety of options. Yoga wasn't a good fit. Walking meditation
felt better, but still too stagnant. I am a high-energy person, and I tend to
carry stress in my body. So, I felt like I need to use my whole body and move
as much of it as possible for this to work. I tried many things and found two
activities that were the winners. The first was running. I could run at the
lake near my home and focus on the feeling of impact in my feet and legs, while
also focusing on my thoughts and the feelings I experienced as I ran. Having
grown up in an abusive home, this was a powerful practice for me. As a child,
running was a safe haven for me. It let me experience a feeling of freedom as I
flew down our dirt road with my long hair flying behind me in the wind. I was
required to keep my hair neatly bound in a tight bun at all times, which caused
bad headaches. So that freeing of my hair was very powerful. The second
activity that helped was boxing. It helped me diffuse a lot of energy, and also
process anger and frustration in a way that did not harm me, or the people
toward whom I felt anger. This was such a powerful and healing practice, that
after two years and regular therapy sessions, I rarely become angry with
anyone. 
 
So, when deciding how to teach mindfulness and meditation to
students, I think it is important to have several options available. I've
worked in schools where the majority of the students are members of rival
gangs, inner-city schools where most students are from working middle-class
families, and magnet schools where we have students from very wealthy families,
students who won full-tuition scholarships, but are living in homeless
shelters, and refugees. The odds of having only students who are able to learn
mindfulness and meditation in a calm and relaxing environment are not great.
Most of my students come from traumatic backgrounds and are still living in
trauma. Many of them have lived in multiple homes, experienced the death of a
family member or close friend, and even experienced violence, genocide, and
other things most of us can only imagine.
